⏰ 18-MINUTE AMRAP ⏰

Grab a set of dumbbells, set a timer for 18 minutes and let’s WORK! 

Do as many rounds of these four exercises as you can for 18 minutes. Awesome form ALWAYS comes before moving faster to get more rounds in. 💪

1️⃣ 20 overhead walking lunges 
2️⃣ 10 alternating kneeling rows + a push up 
3️⃣ 15 dumbbell front squats 
4️⃣ 15 dumbbell toe tap crunches 

This one is a sneaky shoulder burner. 🔥 If you find your shoulders really fatiguing as the workout goes on, you can drop the weight to your chest on the walking lunges. You can also do bodyweight toe tap crunches and lose the dumbbell. 

Let me know what you think and how many rounds you get! 👊

❤️‍🔥 CORE CHALLENGE ❤️‍🔥

I have two fun and different core exercises for you to try! Both incorporate a yoga block for a big core challenge. 

Try 10 reps of each to start! 

1️⃣ bent knee v-up + low boat to vent knee v-up + hollow body with overhead extension. You’ll pass the block from balancing on your shins to reaching overhead. This is a good one for the core strength and coordination work! 
2️⃣ block squeeze crunch with overhead reach. Be sure to do 10 reps on each side. 

Repeat for as many rounds as you’d like. 

Also fun to teach in your yoga classes or do with your PT clients for my fellow yoga teachers and trainers! 🤗

💜 6 YOGA POSES TO HELP YOU DIGEST + REST BEFORE BED 💜 

Most of us are familiar with the term “fight or flight.” It’s the sympathetic nervous system response to stress that causes our hearts to race, adrenaline to surge and senses to go into overdrive. 

Fight or flight is incredibly useful in situations where we’re in danger and need to act quickly but we were never meant to live in the chronic activated stress states that have become the norm these days. 

Did you know that the opposing energy to fight or flight is “digest and rest?” It’s the parasympathetic nervous system response that serves as a break to help slow us down after the danger has passed. When we digest and rest, our heart rates slow down, our breathing gets deeper and slower and digestion is stimulated. 

Most of us need to actively practice ways to digest and rest and can do this through things like yoga, breathwork, gentle exercise, quality sleep, meditation, massage, laughter, singing, hugging or cuddling and more. ☺️

I also love pairing @florastor Florastor Select Digest & Rest 2-in-1 probiotic and sleep supplement with these yoga poses. It supports my digestive health through #probiotics to flush out bad bacteria and boost good! Florastor also contains melatonin to help promote restful and restorative sleep.

Here are six yoga poses to do before bed to promote digestion. 🧘🏻‍♀️

1️⃣ Legs up the wall - this pose is the holy grail of digest and rest. Hold for at least 5 minutes. I like to place my hands on my body for extra grounding. 
2️⃣ Prone half frog - really focus on soft belly breathing in this pose. Hold for 2 minutes on each side. 
3️⃣ Supine twist - hold for 2 minutes on each side. 
4️⃣ Supported side lying - draw one or both knees into the chest. Hold on the left side only for 2-5 minutes. 
5️⃣ Table twist -a gentle inversion combined with a twist. Hold 1 minute on each side. 
6️⃣ Knee into chest - hold on each side for 1-2 minutes. Option to elevate hips on a pillow.

🎆 ONE DUMBBELL TOTAL BODY 🎆

The first workout of 2023 is here and it’s a short but challenging 15 minute total body dumbbell workout. You have four compound movements that will strengthen your whole body while keeping your heart rate up. 

The idea is to cycle through all four movements with no rest for a big four minute push. You’ll then rest 90 seconds and start on the next four minute push for a total of three rounds. 

Sound fun? 😬 Grab one heavy dumbbell and let’s get to work! 

Movement details ⬇️

Alternating single arm kettlebell swing 
Single arm thruster (30 seconds each side)
Alternating single arm squat snatch
Alternating push up side plank

Of course you can modify this workout by doing the movements for reps instead of time, or by adding more rounds. I’d say 8-12 reps would be an ideal range. 

Let me know if you have questions and what you think! 👊

Here’s a four-movement glute activation sequence that is a perfect warm up for strength training lower body or for runners looking for extra glute work. 

All you need is a mini band, something to lean on and something to sit on. 

Start with the band above your ankles and do…
10 two-step lateral shuffles (each trip right and left is one rep)
10rear leg lifts, each leg

Move the band above the knees and do…
20 seated hip abduction pulse outs 
15 banded hip thrusts 

One round is plenty if you’re moving on to other lifts. If this is your only glute workout, you can do 2-3 rounds total.

🍌 PEANUT BUTTER CHOCOLATE CHIP BANANA BREAD 🍌

If you love peanut butter + chocolate as much as I do, you’re going to want to bake this banana bread ASAP. Possibly one of the best banana breads that I’ve ever baked…and I have quite a few delicious recipes on my blog! 

INGREDIENTS
3 ripe bananas 
1/3 cup cane or white sugar 
1/3 cup brown sugar 
6 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted
1/2 cup plain Greek yogurt
1/2 cup natural peanut butter (I used salted)
2 large eggs 
1 teaspoon vanilla
1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
1 teaspoon baking soda
1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
1/2 teaspoon salt
1 cup chocolate chips 

DIRECTIONS
1. Preheat oven to 350 and prepare a 9X5 loaf pan by lining with parchment paper, leaving overhangs on the sides
2. In the bowl of a stand mixer with paddle attachment or using a handheld mixer, mash bananas until they’re a thick paste. Add sugars, melted butter, yogurt, and peanut butter and mix on medium speed. Add eggs and vanilla and mix until just combined - don’t over mix!
3. In a separate bowl, whisk together flour, baking soda, cinnamon and salt. 
4. Add to wet ingredients with mixed on low speed until just combined. 
5. Fold in chocolate chips. 
6. Bake for 50-60 minutes. Baking times will vary. May take a little longer but don’t over bake! 
7. Let cool in pan for a few mins and then lift out using parchment and cool completely on a wire rack. 

Enjoy. The crispy edges are my fave when it’s still warm. 🤤

This is the BEST basic granola recipe! 🤩

The ratio of sweet + salty is perfection. The texture is a contrast of soft + chewy and crispy. If you like granola with big clusters - you’ll love this one! 

My dad introduced me to this granola years ago and we’ve all been hooked ever since. He recently updated his base recipe/method and it’s better than ever. 

Here are the details! 

INGREDIENTS
3 cups oats (rolled, not quick) 
1/3 cup brown sugar, packed
1 teaspoon kosher salt
1/3 cup coconut oil, melted (can also use canola or avocado)
1/3 cup honey + 1 tablespoon
2/3 cup raisins (I used a mix of golden and regular but use whatever you like – you could also mix in other dried fruit)
2/3 cup mixed nuts of choice (pecans, pistachios, pepitas, cashews, walnuts, flaxseed, etc.)

DIRECTIONS

1️⃣ Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Line a baking sheet with a Silpat mat or parchment paper.
2️⃣ Stir together dry ingredients until combined. (Oats, sugar, salt)
Add in coconut oil and honey and mix until combined.
3️⃣ Place mixture on a baking sheet. Spread it to about 3/4 inches thick but be sure to keep it all together in a big rectangle. Do not spread out all over baking sheet.
4️⃣ Bake for 30-35 minutes and remove baking sheet from oven.
5️⃣ Place raisins in original mixing bowl and toss with reserved 1 tablespoon of honey. Pour baked granola back into the mixing bowl and stir well to incorporate raisins.
6️⃣ Place mixture back on baking sheet, again spreading to about 3/4 inch thickness and keeping it all together. Let cool on pan for 45 minutes to an hour, or until completely cooled and set.
7️⃣ Break into clusters and store in an airtight container. Mixture keeps for 7-10 days.

This courageous inquiry has rewarded me lately with some of the deepest and most comfortable backbends that I’ve done in over five years. 

I am mostly just here to remind you that most of us are excellent storytellers but is that story true? And is it aligned with how you want to feel?

💡 TRY THIS EXERCISE!!! 💡

Have you ever done a seated good morning? This exercise has many amazing benefits for the posterior chain! 

1️⃣ builds strength in the low back, glutes and hamstrings
2️⃣ increases dynamic flexibility in the hips and hamstrings - this can help relieve low back pain 
3️⃣ improves hip extension power - this is important because you need strong hip extension for things like walking, running, jumping, swimming and simply standing up from sitting. 
4️⃣ strengthens the isometric position of your back arch - used in lifts such as cleans, snatches, squats + rows
5️⃣ excellent for practicing slow and controlled movements in the posterior chain

HOW TO DO A SEATED GOOD MORNING 

First things first, start with bodyweight only! Place your hands behind your head with fingertips at the ears. Only add weight after you’ve mastered the form - and even then you’ll want to keep it relatively light. I am doing 45 lbs here and it’s the heaviest I’ll go. This movement does not need to be heavy to be effective. 

Straddle a bench and place a barbell in back squat position or fingertips behind ears. Knees bent, feet flat on the floor and knees out a bit wider with toes turned out slightly. 

Brace your trunk and set your back in extension. Slowly hinge at the hips reaching your chest forward and keeping hips grounded. Lean as far forward as you can without losing the back extension position. Press through your heels and slowly rise back up keeping the same form. 

Be mindful not to rely on the low back to lower and lift you and really use the hips. Also, keep your head and gaze in a neutral position and don’t look up and take the head out of alignment with your neck. 

It is SUPER helpful to film yourself doing these to check form. 

HOW MANY? 

3 sets of 6-10 reps

🎃🍌 PUMPKIN SPICE BANANA MUFFINS 🍌🎃

The softest, fluffiest banana muffins packed with pumpkin spice flavor. Made with a mixture of whole wheat and white flours and no refined sugars! Perfect for breakfast, snacking or packing in lunch boxes. 

RECIPE ⬇️

1 cup all purpose flour
1 cup whole wheat flour
1 teaspoon baking soda
1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
1 teaspoon pumpkin pie spice
3/4 teaspoon salt
2 ripe, spotty medium bananas
1 cup pumpkin puree
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/3 cup coconut sugar
1/3 cup maple syrup
2 large eggs at room temperature
1 teaspoon vanilla
1/3 cup plain yogurt

1️⃣ Preheat oven to 425 degrees F. Line a 12-count muffin pan with liners or spray with nonstick spray. I like to do both…use liners and give them a quick spray.
2️⃣ In a medium bowl, whisk together flours, baking soda, cinnamon, pumpkin pie spice and salt together. Set aside.
3️⃣ In a stand mixer fitted with the paddle attachment (or in a large bowl using a hand mixer), mash bananas on medium speed.
4️⃣ Keep the mixer on medium speed and mix in pumpkin puree, melted coconut oil, coconut sugar, maple syrup, eggs, vanilla extract and yogurt.
5️⃣ Reduce mixer speed to medium low and slowly add dry ingredients. Mix until just combined, careful not to overmix. You may have to stop and scrape down the sides of the bowl with a spatula once or twice. Batter will be thick.
6️⃣ Spoon into prepared muffin pan, filling each cup nearly to the top.
7️⃣ Bake at 425 for 5 minutes and then reduce oven temperature to 350 (resist the urge to open the oven door!) and bake for another 15-18 minutes. Total baking time is about 20-23 minutes.
8️⃣ Allow muffins to cool in the pan for about 5 minutes and then remove and place on a wire rack to cool completely.
9️⃣ Store in an airtight container at room temperature for 1-2 days or wrap individually and store in the freezer for 3-4 months.

🏃🏻‍♀️🧘🏻‍♀️ HAMSTRINGS FOR RUNNERS + YOGIS 🧘🏻‍♀️🏃🏻‍♀️

This eccentric hamstring exercise is a must for you! I will be honest, in my 20+ years of running and 14+ years of practicing yoga, I’ve had my fair share of hamstring issues. One thing that is so important to remember is how important it is to not just stretch but STRENGTHEN as well. 

Eccentric hamstring training is a great way to strengthen the hamstring with time under tension in a lengthened state. One simple way to do this is with a sliding disc or towel on a hardwood floor. 

HOW TO DO IT: 
Start in a glute bridge with arms crossed over the chest and both heels grounded. Place slider under one heel. Slowly to a count of 3-5, drive through the heel and extend the foot out, holding the glute bridge throughout. Lower the hips and return back to starting position. Repeat 4-8 reps. 

MAKE IT HARDER: hold a glute bridge with both heels on sliders. Slowly extend both heels out at the same time to a count of 3-5. At the end of the extension, lower hips down and return to starting position.

THE HARDEST:
As I am showing in this video, lift the other leg off the ground to make this a single leg eccentric hamstring exercise. SO HARD. ☠️ Start with 3 rounds of just 4-5 reps on each side.

Thank you @blue_athletic_performance for the inspiration on this leg-lifted variation. Holy 🔥.

Part 2: Mobility Exercises to help build range of motion and improve active mobility.

We found that her rotation wasn’t bad passively, but with how painful it was to roll the tissue on the lacrosse ball, it is common that tissue that sensitive is not firing the way that it should.

When I see this issue, I like to use positional isometrics to help build awareness on how to fire the muscles that have been getting neglected. We first used a sleeper stretch for internal rotation and added PAILS contraction holds to improve neural connection to the stretch. Then we turned over and worked external rotation isometrics to help fired the back of the shoulder in an isolated way. This will help her be able to find that tissue better during overhead strength exercises.

Working rotation first is a common way I like to approach shoulder dysfunction. If a shoulder can’t rotate, it is going to have a hard time in the other ranges of motion as well. It is important to understand where your deficits are and how to choose the best starting point for what you are dealing with!

“The child within us is the child we have to raise. The core of conscious parenting at a simplistic level is the parent who dares to raise themselves first — who looks at the dynamic they have with their children as a mirror to all their own unresolved baggage. So instead of jumping forth and pouncing on the child when they are feeling any sort of anxiety, they look at this moment as an opportunity to heal that which has risen from their own past.”

@doctorshefali’s book The Conscious Parent has been the single most powerful book of my parenting journey. I listened to a conversation with she and @oprah when I was running yesterday about her newest book and the words I quoted above have stuck to me like glue.

No doubt that being Finn’s mom has been life’s greatest teacher but it’s also been an incredible healer - and truly shined a light on wounds, triggers and generational family patterns that I deeply wish not to pass on to him. 

This is not easy work but I know it’s the most important work I’ll ever do. Today I was triggered to tears and it had absolutely nothing to do with my sweet boy. I will keep talking about social anxiety and introversion because I think social connections and meaningful friendships are such an important part of overall and mental health — especially in this post-pandemic world. 🫶

And it was just perfect. I had the best time, felt so relaxed and ended up staying for over three hours. Home now with a very full and happy heart. 

It is REALLY hard sometimes for me to get out of the mental loop of anticipation/dread but I am almost always SO glad that I did when I push myself to show up. ❤️

Today was a weird day. School was out for weather. Said weather was high winds, flash flooding, tornado warnings and thunderstorms…in January. A tree is falling down at my rental house. Somehow all six of my personal training clients showed up for their sessions this morning but everyone was a bit out of sorts. I showed up to teach yoga tonight feeling activated and wondering how in the world I would uplift others. 

But on the way to teach the skies started to clear. I could see glimpses of clear sky among the dark clouds and it reminded me of the Pema Chodron quote that I reference so often…

“You are the sky. Everything else — it’s just the weather.”

Our lives are full of weather ranging from category five hurricanes to quick tornadoes to flash floods to gentle rains. One thing is always certain - the weather always passes and we are left with calm blue skies. That is always inside of us - sometimes it just gets all mucked up. 

I shared where I was at when I opened class and taught from that place. After thousands of hours of teaching I have learned that there is no other choice. Class was beautiful and we all left feeling connected and uplifted. We are NEVER alone in our weather. ❤️

And now I am on the couch rewatching Scandal again from episode one because I need some Olivia Pope energy in my life -it’s handled! 👊
